<br>
1 Indy = 10$ = right for 1 raid<br>
60 People Guild = 600$ = right for 1 raid<br>
<br>
It is infact<br>
<br>
1 Indy = $10 x 60 others people on the raid, from various backgrounds = $600= right for 1 raid<br>
<br>
60 People Guild = 600$ = right for 1 raid<br>
<br>
IE $600guild picked raiders=$600indy picked raiders, the only actual difference is one of WHO gets to do the picking. X number of raiders still go to Z raid slots, be they indy or guild.<br>
<br>
The real problem that needs to be addressed is this situation where guilds count as one player for bookings and yet various indies can theoretically act as a pseudo guild inviteing each other but avoiding the above booking restriction. That is what needs solveing. This inequity will not be fixed by swinging hard the other way with an even greater inequity.<br>
<br>
<br>
The fact is we are talking about a limited resource with a large demand, There are only two alternatives in these types of situations, either everyone has an equal opurtunity to the resource by even division or you deny some portion (disorganised minorities are popular favourites here) access to the resource in order to increase another groups &quot;wealth&quot;. This later case is what the &quot;ban indies&quot; idea  is promoteing, This is not a good solution, it will lead to major trouble. Take a look at any historical revolution if you dont believe me.<br>
<br>
The answer is to be found in the equal share, however we arent quite there with what we have now.<br>
<br>
